Valentine

Target IP: 10.129.149.178

Scanning


There are three ports open on the target machine: SSH, HTTP, and HTTPs. The vhost name for this is valentine.htb. I appended this name inside the /etc/hosts file.


Running nmap valentine --script vuln shows the target machine is vulnerable to the Heartbleed bug!


More information about the vulnerability for port 443.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this application. Digging through the source-code does not reveal anything useful.


Doing a directory search using the command gobuster dir -u http://valentine.htb -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/big.txt against this application returns the interesting result above.


The /dev/ is an interesting directory as it contains the two files as shown above.


The /notes.txt contains the message above. It sounds like the decoder/encoder is possibly sending sensitive data. And the /hype_key contains hex bytes.


I copied the content of hype_key on my machine and decoded it using the command cat hype_key | xxd -r -p and obtained a SSH key. The name of this file gives us a hint. Does the SSH key belong to user hype?

Exploitation


Performing a check against the target machine using the auxiliary module scanner/ssl/openssl_heartbleed shows the target is vulnerable to the Heartbleed bug.



This exploit is available using searchsploit. I copied the exploit to my machine. I ran the exploit against the machine and received a base64 string aGVhcnRibGVlZGJlbGlldmV0aGVoeXBlCg==.


Decoding the base64 outputs the string above.



I decrypted the key I found earlier, and then logged in as the user hype with the decrypted key. Now I have a foothold on the machie as the user hype.

Privilege Escalation


Looks like the user used tmux before according to the .bash_history file.


There is an active tmux session at the moment when running ps -aux.


Gaining a root shell is simple by entering the command /usr/bin/tmux -S /.devs/dev_sess.

Flags


The user.txt flag once I gained a foothold on the machine.


The root.txt flag once I gained a root shell on the machine.
